'''Jan Tschichold''' (  ,  &ndash;   , ) was a , book designer, teacher and writer.
Tschichold was the son of a provincial , and he was trained in . This  background and calligraphic training set him apart from almost all other noted typographers of the time, since they had inevitably trained in  or the s. 
Tschichold's artisan background may help explain why he never worked with handmade papers and custom fonts as many typographers did, preferring instead to use stock fonts on a careful choice from commercial paper stocks. After the election of  in Germany, all designers had to register with the Ministry of Culture, and all teaching posts were threatened for anyone who was sympathetic to . Armed  arrested him and his wife in , and  posters were found in his flat, casting him under suspicion of collaboration with communists. All copies of Tschichold's books were seized by the  ''"for the protection of the German people"''.{{Fact|date=April 2007}} After six weeks a policeman somehow found him tickets for , and he and his family managed to escape Nazi Germany. Apart from short visits to  in - (at the invitation of the ), and - (at the invitation of , the British typographer, with whom he worked on the design of ), he lived the rest of his life in Switzerland.
