Tschichold had converted to  design principles in  after visiting the first   exhibition. He became a leading advocate of Modernist design: first with an influential  magazine supplement; then a  personal exhibition; then with his most noted work ''Die neue Typographie''. This book was a manifesto of modern design, in which he condemned all fonts but  (called 'Grotesk' in Germany).  He also favoured non-centered design (e.g., on title pages), and codified many other Modernist design rules.  He advocated the use of standardised paper sizes for all printed matter, and made some of the first clear explanations of the effective use of different sizes and weights of type in order to quickly and easily convey information. This book was followed with a series of practical manuals on the principles of  which had a wide influence among ordinary workers and printers in Germany. Yet, despite his visits to England just before the war, only about four articles by Tschichold had been translated into English by .
Although ''Die neue Typographie'' remains a classic, Tschichold slowly abandoned his rigid beliefs from around  onwards (e.g. his Saskia typeface of 1932, and his acceptance of classical Roman typefaces for body-type) as he moved back towards  in print design.{{Fact|date=April 2007}} He later condemned ''Die neue Typographie'' as too extreme. He also went so far as to condemn Modernist design in general as being  and inherently ic. 
Between - Tschichold lived in England where he oversaw the redesign of 500 s published by , leaving them with a standardised set of typographic rules, the ''Penguin Composition Rules''.<ref>{{cite web
